<TEXT>
robert pirosh whose 1949 screenplay 
battleground won an academy award and who cowrote the marx 
brothers classic a day at the races died monday of heart 
failure he was 79 
priosh who wrote produced or directed a dozen wellknown films 
and a similar number of television series remained active through 
his later years most recently teaching writing at the university 
of southern california 
his 1949 oscarwinning drama was based on the fighting between 
german and allied troops at the battle of the bulge where he 
fought with the 320th infantry in the 35th division at bastogne 
belgium 
he was writer or cowriter of the films a day at the races 
i married a witch hell is for heroes a gathering of 
eagles whats so bad about feeling good go for broke 
and many more 
as a tv writer he wrote the pilot programs for laramie and 
combat he also wrote segments of hawaii fiveo ellery 
queen mannix bonanza ironside the waltons and 
barnaby jones among others 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
j willcox dunn a retired newspaper 
editor and publisher who crusaded against gambling died friday he 
was 91 
dunn a native of suffolk in 1952 established the weekly 
princess anne free press serving virginia beach and princess anne 
county he was its editor publisher and sole owner until he ceased 
its publication on retiring in 1962 
in 1958 dunn was awarded the national elijah parish lovejoy 
award for courage in journalism for his opposition to political 
corruption and racketeering in the region 
he received his law degree from the university of virginia in 
1922 he practiced law in lynchburg and worked for union carbide in 
new york city before moving to virginia beach in 1936 where he 
entered the real estate business 
in 1935 he married lelia baker taylor of norfolk his wife died 
in 1962 
survivors include a daughter margaret t dunn of 
charlottesville a son joseph w dunn jr of virginia beach two 
sisters mary d wallace of richmond and martha d lyon of warren 
mich and three grandchildren 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
thomas harold hal cunningham the 
retired editor and publisher of the llano news and a former 
president of the texas press association died saturday of cardiac 
arrest he was 81 
a native of henrietta texas he earned his bachelors and 
masters degrees in journalism at the university of texas in austin 
after managing camp lajunta in hunt texas in the late 1940s 
and early 50s cunningham in 1954 became news editor of the 
kerrville mountain sun a post he held for five years before 
purchasing the llano news a weekly which he published for 25 
years he retired in 1983 
cunningham served as president of the state texas press 
association from 198283 
cunningham is survived by his wife hazel cunningham of llano 
and a nephew 
</TEXT>
