<TEXT>
gunmen believed to be moslem 
bandits kidnapped a french missionary and his niece in the southern 
philippines and police killed one of the abductors in a firefight 
police and church officials said sunday 
the rev michel de gigord and his 29yearold niece benedict 
were abducted saturday after leaving saint marys convent in 
marawi 510 miles southeast of manila said the rev leo laviste 
vicar general of archdiocese of iligan and marawi cities 
laviste said they have not yet heard from the kidnappers 
laviste said de gigord was driving his niece toward iligan 
city 20 miles to the north when six armed men stopped their car 
near the convents gate 
one of the gunmen shoved de gigord from the drivers seat and 
followed by a jeep boarded by the other kidnappers drove the 
priests car to the shores of nearby lanao lake and sent the two 
victims by boat to an island in the lake laviste said 
neighbors who saw the abduction immediately informed authorities 
in the convent who notified the local police 
pursuing policemen engaged in a gunbattle with some of the 
gunmen who had been left behind on the lakeshore killing one of 
them marawi police station commander capt jalandoni cota he said 
the others escaped 
police also recovered de gigords vehicle abandoned by the 
kidnappers there was no report on what happened to the kidnappers 
jeep 
sources at the lanao del sur provincial military and police 
headquarters said the victims have been moved by the kidnappers to 
the town of madamba 23 miles west of marawi late sunday morning 
provincial commander lt col omar manabilang has sought the 
assistance of the mayors of madamba and two adjacent towns and 
local moslem religious leaders to help rescue the priest and his 
niece the sources said 
de gigord a member of the paris foreign mission has been 
chaplain at the mindanao state university in marawi for the past 10 
years he was kidnapped by moslem bandits in february 1985 and held 
captive for about a month in their mountain hideout but was 
released unharmed 
