inspectors were at an aspen ski resort 
sunday to determine why a chairlift slid 35 feet backward causing 
five skiers to fall or jump to the ground and leaving 200 others 
stranded 
a 14yearold evergreen girl broke her back in saturdays 
accident at the buttermilk ski resort and remained hospitalized 
authorities said 
four people were treated for minor injuries three of the 
stranded skiers were treated for hypothermia and released 
the cable on the milelong lift slid 35 feet in eight seconds 
before an emergency brake caught hold aspen skiing co officials 
said 
some of the stranded skiers were stuck aloft for up to two hours 
as ski patrol members evacuated the lift using ladders and a tbar 
attached to a handheld rope officials said 
resort officials did not know how far the skiers fell because 
the height varies as the chair moves up the mountain they said 
none of the drops was major 
it was the first chairlift accident at buttermilk since the ski 
area opened in 1958 said terri hartroberts an aspen skiing co 
spokeswoman the lift built and installed in 1969 by herron poma 
is a fixedgrip chairlift a common design in which each chair is 
permanently attached to the lift cable 
</TEXT>
