<TEXT>
a widely watched measure of the labor market 
sent out weak signals in november a business research group said 
in a report for release today 
the conference board said its helpwanted index dropped six 
points in november erasing almost all of octobers fivepoint gain 
the seasonally adjusted index fell to 145 in november from 
octobers 151 and septembers 146 the november reading was 11 
points lower than the year earlier level 
as the decade ends the economy is not now growing fast enough 
to keep up with the rise in the workingage population 
conference board economist ken goldstein said consequently new 
entrants or reentrants to the work force spend a little more 
time finding jobs he said 
clearly this is a weakened labor market but not a declining 
one he said noting that the us unemployment rate probably 
will edge up in 1990 
the jobless rate was 54 percent in november up from 53 
percent in october and the same as in november of 1988 goldstein 
said the rate may rise to 58 percent by june 
job advertising volume fell in seven of the nine regions of the 
country measured by the new yorkbased research group only the 
east south central and mountain regions showed increases while new 
england continued to be the weakest as it has been for several 
months 
the helpwanted index is based on ad volume in 51 major 
newspapers across the country the conference board says ad volume 
has proven to be sensitive to labor market conditions and provides 
a gauge of change in the supply of jobs 
</TEXT>
