<DOCNO> AP891231-0048 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the investment portfolio of the average small 
investor tripled in the 1980s aided by the booming stock market 
according to an index compiled by money magazine 
the magazine said its small investor index grew 2005 percent 
during the decade 
at that rate holdings worth 14791 on dec 31 1979 grew by 
the end of 1989 to 44439 which the magazine says is the size of 
the typical individual investors portfolio today the index 
assumes that all earnings were reinvested 
the gain for the decade was equivalent to an 116 percent annual 
return compared with a 6 percent return during the 1970s money 
said after inflation which averaged 51 percent a year in the 
1980s investors saw real annual profits of 65 percent during the 
1970s they actually lost 13 percent a year after inflation the 
magazine says 
the growth of investment portfolios in the 1980s resulted 
primarily from the longest bull market in stocks since the 1950s 
money says 
small investors also benefitted from the boom in moneymarket 
mutual funds which allowed them to earn two to four percentage 
points more on their cash than in the 1970s when they generally 
kept cash in lowyielding passbook savings accounts 
for 1989 small investors saw their portfolios increase by 145 
percent on average according to the money index again much of 
the increase was due to the runup in stocks 
</TEXT>
